00:16:47,975 --> 00:16:53,919
[SPEAKER_05]: So just just to clear up confusion, I think that the version with legal documents on it was an earlier version of the ordinance.

172
00:16:56,120 --> 00:16:57,060
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Councillor Collins.

173
00:16:57,220 --> 00:16:58,061
[SPEAKER_06]: Going to Councillor Seng.

174
00:16:59,065 --> 00:17:01,466
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Councilor Collins for that run through.

175
00:17:02,687 --> 00:17:15,173
[SPEAKER_01]: The amendment I was going to propose, I think it came to my mind when I was looking at the legal comments that were sent and it seems like you guys have already addressed it.

176
00:17:15,193 --> 00:17:17,474
[SPEAKER_01]: It was the one regarding emails.

177
00:17:17,574 --> 00:17:22,717
[SPEAKER_01]: And as a young person, oftentimes it's easier for us to find documents via email.

178
00:17:23,877 --> 00:17:28,480
[SPEAKER_01]: It's easier for us to, oftentimes we misplace papers,

179
00:17:29,560 --> 00:17:31,321
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's not only a young person thing.

180
00:17:31,541 --> 00:17:33,922
[SPEAKER_01]: It might happen to anyone.

181
00:17:33,983 --> 00:17:39,605
[SPEAKER_01]: And so having it in record and email is certainly, I think, beneficial.

182
00:17:39,685 --> 00:17:42,667
[SPEAKER_01]: And your subcommittee already made that edit.

183
00:17:42,927 --> 00:17:44,308
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm very grateful for that.

184
00:17:44,968 --> 00:17:53,052
[SPEAKER_01]: I also wanted to note, I'm very grateful for the lens that you guys have put on equity as well, and making sure that all residents

185
00:17:54,772 --> 00:18:16,856
[SPEAKER_01]: have will have access to this ordinance, the benefits of this ordinance, the language stuff that you guys as a subcommittee have put in there has been, I think is very helpful and very, I think very shows how much we as a council are paying attention to issues of equity and access.

186
00:18:17,356 --> 00:18:19,436
[SPEAKER_01]: So I just wanted to express my thanks for that as well.

187
00:18:21,097 --> 00:18:21,417
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

188
00:18:21,877 --> 00:18:22,497
[SPEAKER_06]: Vice President Behrs.

189
00:18:23,858 --> 00:18:25,039
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, Madam President.

190
00:18:25,119 --> 00:18:26,740
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you, Councilor Collins.

191
00:18:27,520 --> 00:18:31,363
[SPEAKER_00]: And thank you to all the staff who've been with us through this process so far.

192
00:18:31,383 --> 00:18:40,088
[SPEAKER_00]: I just again want to really emphasize and thank the PDS office Board of Health and everyone else who's worked with us on this.

193
00:18:41,732 --> 00:18:51,597
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, it's really, and I think this is, you know, we talked about fines we talked about enforcement but really the conversation that we had in the subcommittee meeting is that, you know, this is primarily to start an education tool.

194
00:18:52,098 --> 00:19:03,104
[SPEAKER_00]: And, you know, the goal is to get this information out as broadly as possible to as many people as possible so that they have the information that they need about their rights and and duties around.

195
00:19:04,345 --> 00:19:05,145
[SPEAKER_00]: Housing stability.

196
00:19:06,545 --> 00:19:22,348
[SPEAKER_00]: So just wanted to put that out there to say that on the two issues that we raised in our last subcommittee meeting, you know, one, I think it's clear around whether we can directly send any fines from this ordinance to the affordable housing trust.

197
00:19:22,368 --> 00:19:23,068
[SPEAKER_00]: The answer is no.

198
00:19:24,568 --> 00:19:26,689
[SPEAKER_00]: So I don't think that that's gonna require further amendment.

199
00:19:27,269 --> 00:19:33,750
[SPEAKER_00]: I do think that it would be, you know, I don't know if we wanna include it or just make a side recommendation that,

200
00:19:34,372 --> 00:19:42,154
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, the mayor, if any fines are accrued under this ordinance, that the mayor appropriate them to the Affordable Housing Trust Fund if and when that is created.

201
00:19:42,894 --> 00:19:48,035
[SPEAKER_00]: But I'd really be open to kind of not trying to shoehorn that into the ordinance in any way.

202
00:19:48,055 --> 00:19:58,737
[SPEAKER_00]: And then secondly, when it comes to, you know, liens for unpaid fines, I think my preference would be that we address that at a later date if necessary, considering that the

203
00:19:59,563 --> 00:20:06,009
[SPEAKER_00]: purpose here is going to be really educational and not, you know, leaning hard on enforcement, at least to start.

204
00:20:06,490 --> 00:20:16,360
[SPEAKER_00]: And if we find after some time of implementation that there is a need to go back and amend this, you know, then I would be comfortable certainly doing that at that time.

205
00:20:17,901 --> 00:20:22,105
[SPEAKER_00]: And finally, I just want to say that to Councillor Sang's point, another goal of this is that

206
00:20:22,952 --> 00:20:26,254
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, a lot of this information is available on the city website.

207
00:20:26,755 --> 00:20:45,928
[SPEAKER_00]: But I think also having a copy of this specific notice be available on the city website and be available in different offices around the city is another way that we're hopefully going to be able to get this information out and use the work product that's created with the notification documents to reach people who may otherwise not have this information.

208
00:20:46,068 --> 00:20:50,311
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's just my thinking on the outstanding questions as they are.

209
00:20:50,892 --> 00:20:51,192
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

210
00:20:52,493 --> 00:20:53,433
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you, Vice President Behrs.

211
00:20:55,434 --> 00:20:56,034
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Collins.

212
00:20:58,394 --> 00:20:59,274
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you, President Morrell.

213
00:20:59,815 --> 00:21:01,155
[SPEAKER_05]: I appreciate the discussion around this.

214
00:21:01,435 --> 00:21:12,297
[SPEAKER_05]: I would tend to agree with Vice President Behrs on how to proceed with the two questions around how do we dispense with fines that Attorney Everett was able to answer for us.

215
00:21:13,797 --> 00:21:16,158
[SPEAKER_05]: It seems like the issue of how to deal with liens, that's

216
00:21:17,458 --> 00:21:24,871
[SPEAKER_05]: Maybe maybe more of a systemic not systemic that's that's a question that could be applied to a multitude of ordinances in the city.

217
00:21:25,673 --> 00:21:27,596
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't feel the need to attach it to this project.

218
00:21:32,832 --> 00:21:49,590
[SPEAKER_05]: I appreciate the recentering on the theme of this conversation and the theme of this ordinance in general, which is to make sure that, you know, with, while we're devoting city resources to this project, that that's in service of housing stability, it's in service of making sure that people know their rights, it's in service of making sure that people

219
00:21:50,270 --> 00:21:51,251
[SPEAKER_05]: know their resources.

220
00:21:52,272 --> 00:21:54,634
[SPEAKER_05]: City staff works hard to make sure that people know these already.

221
00:21:54,654 --> 00:22:00,939
[SPEAKER_05]: The point here is to cross pollinate with all that work that's already done and have another tool for getting it out into the city.

222
00:22:01,780 --> 00:22:08,866
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think that it's the right use of our focus to make sure that city staff are able to

223
00:22:11,156 --> 00:22:15,299
[SPEAKER_05]: use this to continue getting the word out and adding to that toolbox.

224
00:22:16,360 --> 00:22:23,666
[SPEAKER_05]: And then if the way that we're dealing with fines and enforcement becomes an issue, that can be a conversation that we have in the future.

225
00:22:25,527 --> 00:22:25,827
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

226
00:22:26,388 --> 00:22:27,088
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Carvalho.

227
00:22:28,309 --> 00:22:28,950
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you, Madam President.

228
00:22:29,890 --> 00:22:35,034
[SPEAKER_08]: Do we have a fee, a fine structure yet of what other cities are charging for fines?

229
00:22:39,178 --> 00:22:39,718
[SPEAKER_06]: Councilor Collins.

230
00:22:41,995 --> 00:22:53,999
[SPEAKER_05]: I don't have a comprehensive look, but I know that in the three other housing stability notification ordinances that we reviewed for Cambridge, Somerville, and Boston, their penalty, their enforcement structure was the same as ours.

231
00:22:54,079 --> 00:22:55,460
[SPEAKER_05]: It was a penalty of $300.

232
00:22:55,700 --> 00:23:06,143
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think that that is governed by, I think the state statute is mentioned in the text of the ordinance, but it's statutorily defined.

233
00:23:06,163 --> 00:23:10,125
[SPEAKER_08]: Will this be enforced by the Board of Health or the code enforcement officer?

234
00:23:10,888 --> 00:23:11,368
[SPEAKER_05]: Board of Health.

235
00:23:12,309 --> 00:23:16,130
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

236
00:23:16,310 --> 00:23:18,611
[SPEAKER_07]: Vice President Behrs, is your hand up again or still up?

237
00:23:18,631 --> 00:23:25,233
[SPEAKER_07]: I'll go with still up anyway.

238
00:23:25,253 --> 00:23:26,093
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh, there you go.

239
00:23:26,153 --> 00:23:27,374
[SPEAKER_00]: A little bit of both, sorry.

240
00:23:27,454 --> 00:23:28,154
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay.

241
00:23:29,555 --> 00:23:31,776
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, it's Chapter 40, Section 21B.

242
00:23:31,976 --> 00:23:37,358
[SPEAKER_00]: And that's the, you know, first violation is a written warning and then subsequent violation is $300.

243
00:23:41,593 --> 00:23:43,974
[SPEAKER_06]: Any other discussion or questions from counselors?

244
